I‚Äôm at the DMV renewing my drivers license.

The final step is where it asks you if you are a United States citizen or not. 

Yes, you can get a drivers license in California, if you are here illegally. 

If you came here illegally, and are getting a drivers license, you must check the box that says I am not a citizen, or decline to answer.

The DMV will not register you to vote if you check either of those two boxes. 

If you simply check the box that says you are a citizen, you will be registered to vote. 

It‚Äôs that simple. 

If you are here illegally, and you want to vote, you simply need to check a box.

Yes, that would be illegal, but so is coming here illegally, so why would that bother you?

legacy.description: AI is cool i guess

result.text:
One of the most fun parts of OpenAI is watching people here level up so fast and do such excellent work.

We are operating at a high level across many different disciplines and many of the people doing it have never done it before, and joined us at the beginning of their career.

If you believe in people and give them a lot of responsibility and support (and pick the right people to bet on) you will be surprised on the upside more often than you think.

I would love to see more companies operate this way and think we would all benefit.

(This was also one of the most fun parts of startup investing.)

In case you missed it‚Ä¶

Channel 4 recently commissioned a study on BAME representation in UK advertising. The likely assumption, of course, was that the findings would reinforce the narrative of systemic underrepresentation.

But it backfired‚Äîspectacularly.

When the agency they hired, Tapestry, sent the data back to them, they found that 50% of UK adverts featured black people...

Half of all commercials.

Compared that to the percentage of black people in the UK population: just 4%, according to the 2021 census.

It went on...

People of South Asian descent make up 8% of the population but appeared in 17% of ads. 

East Asians make up 1%, yet were represented in 11% of adverts.

Maybe the media class aren‚Äôt wrong.
We do live in a society riddled with systemic racism. It‚Äôs just not against the races they keep telling us it is.
